I recently picked up N.O.V.A, and was impressed with how they had made such a brilliant immersive FPS experience on a tablet with a touch screen. I've always loved FPS shooters, but the ones I've tried on tablets have been deeply user unfriendly, unless you were playing a sniper, and had time to sight in on targets. Not so with all the GL FPS games - the UI is instinctive and soon has you playing as well as you'd expect with BF, MoH, or CoD on a console. Oh, and the graphics are stunning. The most recent outing sucks, as it's a pay to play scenario, and it's just not worth it; but MC3 and 4 are incredible games, and the first ones that I restarted from the beginning the second I'd finished them. I hope they return to the financial model created in earlier outing for MC6, as right now it's hampered by their own greed.

Each level provides a different a different backrop and there's even a diversity of shooting technologies, i.e. shoot a gun on the ground and firing missiles from a helicopter. So far...no errors. No bugs. No force closes. Update: I'm taking away two stars because the in-app purchase of protective armour only increases protection temporarily. That's a huge rip-off. Ammo I can understand. UPDATE: Latest patch ruined my controls; I had trigger on left, as I prefer, and could move while shooting, now trigger forces aiming.  I was pretty apprehensive about buying this game after all the negative reviews stating it doesn't work on Transformers, but since it's on sale so cheap I figured I'd give it a shot. I've finished several levels with no crashes or performance issues.    The graphics are pretty good but not nearly as pretty as the screenshots suggest. Character models range from acceptable to hideous. Environs range from good to acceptable. Weapon models are pretty good. Not nearly as good looking as Dead Trigger, but the levels are *much* larger.   The maximum aim sensitivity is pretty low, maybe to mask the low framerate... the game appears to be running about 15-20fps - it is a lot harder to aim than it should be because of the terrible framerate. The TF700's Tegra 3 should be able to run this at 60 fps.    A decent knockoff of CoD, but the fact that you effectively can't move while using iron sights seriously hurts my enjoyment of the game. Another complaint I have is the hit area for the on-screen buttons is about four times the visual size of the button.

HOW TO GET MC3 ON YOUR SII!!!!  Your phone should be rooted.  Go to the Android Market and search for "Device Spoofer" It will show up in the APPS list. Buy it and install it. It's $1.50.  Run the app.  Backup current settings using the app.  Select HTC Desire HD in the drop down menu.  Click Spoof Selected Device and reboot.  Now goto the Android Market and search for "Modern Combat 3"......buy it....install it.....ENJOY!!!!!!  I am running it on my SGSII and it has had no problems whatsoever at this point.  If it does crash or have problems later....I figure....what the heck....they will do updates to fix it and I still only have $2.49 in a cool app and game.  SWEET!  I'm using Juggernaut v4.1 from xda-developersDOTcom in case anyone wants to know.  Peace brothers!

Technically it's playable, but the awkwardness of the controls borders on unusable. I respect that it's difficult or even impossible to really give players a way to move, aim and fire all at once without getting at least 3 fingers on the screen, but some spots in the game are staged to make that pretty necessary.  Playing the game feels too stop-and-go because you have to stop trying to move while you try to work out where there are guys to shoot.  I also noticed that there's a bug when you have the option to pick up a new weapon that prevents you from looking around while the button is onscreen.  I know it's not an easy problem to solve, but the controls just make the game frustrating.  I do give credit to the fact that they managed to make the game playback completely smooth on my DesireHD/Inspire which is now well over a year old hardware.
